  "local_port": 47420,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to apply to an RTI?",
  "response": "The **Right to Information (RTI) Act**, enacted in India in 2005, empowers citizens to access information from public authorities, promoting transparency and accountability in government. If you're looking to apply for information under the RTI Act, here's a step-by-step guide to help you through the process:\n\n### 1. **Identify the Public Authority**\n\n- **Determine the Relevant Department**: Identify the government department or public authority that holds the information you seek. Public authorities can include central, state, or local government bodies.\n  \n- **Designated Public Information Officer (PIO)**: Each public authority has a designated PIO responsible for receiving and processing RTI applications. You can typically find contact details on the department's official website or the RTI section of their website.\n\n### 2. **Frame a Clear and Specific Request**\n\n- **Be Specific**: Clearly mention the information you are seeking to avoid ambiguities. Vague or broad requests may lead to delays or refusals.\n\n- **Include Details**: Provide relevant details such as dates, subject matter, or specific documents to help the PIO locate the information efficiently.\n\n### 3. **Draft the RTI Application**\n\nThe application should generally include:\n\n- **Addressed to the Appropriate PIO**: Ensure you're sending the application to the correct PIO of the concerned public authority.\n\n- **Personal Details**: Include your full name, address, and contact information.\n\n- **Details of Information Sought**: Clearly specify the information or documents you are requesting.\n\n- **Fee Details**: Mention the mode of payment for the RTI application fee.\n\nHere\u2019s a basic template:\n\n```\nTo,\nThe Public Information Officer,\n[Name of the Department/Public Authority],\n[Address of the Department/Public Authority].\n\nSubject: Request for Information under the Right to Information Act, 2005\n\nDear Sir/Madam,\n\nI, [Your Full Name], [Your Address], request the following information under the RTI Act, 2005:\n\n[Clearly describe the information you seek, including any relevant details to help locate the information.]\n\nI have enclosed the RTI application fee of [specify amount, e.g., \u20b910] as per the prescribed guidelines.\n\nThank you for your assistance.\n\nYours sincerely,\n[Your Signature]\n[Your Name]\n```\n\n### 4. **Pay the Application Fee**\n\n- **Fee Amount**: The standard fee for an RTI application is \u20b910 in most states. Some states may have different fee structures.\n\n- **Payment Methods**: Payment can typically be made via:\n  - **Demand Draft (DD)**: Payable to the designated authority.\n  - **Postal Order (PO)**.\n  - **Cash**: Some departments accept cash payments.\n  - **Online Portals**: Many public authorities now accept online payments through their RTI portals.\n\n- **Include Payment Proof**: If paying via DD or PO, attach a photocopy of the receipt with your application.\n\n### 5. **Submit the Application**\n\n- **Method of Submission**:\n  - **In Person**: Visit the public authority's office and submit the application directly to the PIO or the designated RTI office.\n  - **By Post**: Send the application to the official address of the public authority.\n  - **Online**: Utilize official RTI portals (if available) to submit your application electronically.\n\n- **Keep Copies**: Always keep a copy of the application and the payment receipt for your records.\n\n### 6. **Await Response Within the Specified Timeframe**\n\n- **Response Time**:\n  - **30 Days**: The public authority is obligated to respond within 30 days from the receipt of the application.\n  - **Urgent Cases**: For information concerning the life or liberty of a person, the response should be within 48 hours.\n  - **State-wise Variations**: Some states might have different timelines, so it's advisable to check the specific provisions applicable in your state.\n\n### 7. **Follow Up and Appeal if Necessary**\n\n- **No Response or Refusal**: If you do not receive a response within the stipulated time or if your request is denied, you have the right to file an appeal.\n\n- **First Appeal**:\n  - **Who to Address**: Typically to the First Appellate Authority within the same public authority.\n  - **Timeline**: Should be filed within 30 days from the expiration of the initial response period.\n\n- **Second Appeal**:\n  - **Higher Authority**: If unsatisfied with the first appeal, you can approach the Central Information Commission or the State Information Commission.\n  - **Timeline**: Should be filed within 90 days from the date of the first appeal's decision.\n\n### 8. **Additional Tips**\n\n- **Language**: Applications can be submitted in English, Hindi, or the official language of the state.\n\n- **Assistance**: If you're unsure about the process, consider seeking assistance from RTI advocacy groups, NGOs, or legal advisors.\n\n- **Be Clear and Concise**: Clearly articulated requests are more likely to yield prompt and accurate responses.\n\n- **Maintain Records**: Keep all correspondence related to your RTI application for future reference.\n\n### Useful Resources\n\n- **Central Information Commission**: [http://cic.gov.in](http://cic.gov.in)\n  \n- **State Information Commissions**: Each state has its own Information Commission. Visit your state's official website for specific details.\n\n- **RTI Online Portals**: Many public authorities have online RTI submission portals. Check the respective department\u2019s official website for more information.\n\nBy following these steps diligently, you can effectively utilize the RTI Act to access the information you need from public authorities.",
